    <segment id="1" parent="50" relname="solutionhood">Should we really think about relativism as a virus that infects people
manifesting itself in intolerance?</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="84" relname="concession"> Again, I am not a relativist</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="84" relname="span"> but I don&apos;t
see how speech codes follow inexorably out of relativism.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="46" relname="span"> The problem is
how you individuate cultures--</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="47" relname="span">are they separate things that can then show
each other tolerance?</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="49" relname="span"> Here is where tolerance--which could be pushed from
some versions of relativism--becomes &quot;separate but equal&quot; tolerance which
becomes repressive tolerance, whether in its defensive forms--</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="nonvolitional-cause">some views
can&apos;t even get to the table</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="48" relname="span"> so tolerance promoters consider coercive
measures--or in its most pernicious form as allegedly promoting free
expression while actually functioning as a way to shut people up.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="85" relname="background">

I&apos;m sure Edwards is aware of this history of the &quot;politically correct&quot;
accusation.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="85" relname="span">  It is nothing less than the trick of the pickpocket who yells
&quot;stop, thief&quot; when he is caught.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="76" relname="span"> Just look at how it functions in public
discourse--</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="circumstance">after it was introduced by a heavily funded right-wing campaign.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="79" relname="span">
And in groups like the NAS now sponsoring a symposium on the attack on
science. </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="78" relname="span"> Critical thought, the crossing of boundaries, the mixing of
natural and human sciences, the growth of &quot;outsider&quot; claims on and interest
in the &quot;inside&quot; of science are condemned as a dogmatic short-circuiting of
insiders&apos; (read as unitary and with well-defined borders) privilege.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="51" relname="span"> A
community--scientific or otherwise--can only seem to have this kind of
coherence by a scapegoating trick.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="81" relname="span">

The connection of relativism and scapegoating universalisms like this is in
fact pretty intimate.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="69" relname="span"> A characteristic of the &quot;new racism&quot; is its
articulation in an idiom of cultural relativism:</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="19" relname="antithesis"> &quot;Immigrant populations in
Europe or the US are just not part of our culture or nation,</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="53" relname="span"> so why don&apos;t
they go back to their own?&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="52" relname="span"> (i.e. they have their own somewhere</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="20" relname="antithesis"> but it ain&apos;t
&quot;here&quot; even though they&apos;ve been &quot;here&quot; for quite some time and even though
they&apos;ve built &quot;here&quot; economically and culturally.) </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="56" relname="span"> Here cultural relativism
tacitly appeals to racism by means of a
reductive analysis of culture. </segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="55" relname="span">Culture reappears in proximity to race or
nation but invokes the tropes of cultural tolerance for the purpose of
reworking notions of citizenship</segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="23" relname="elaboration"> (the expatriate Croatian counts in Croatia
but not a &quot;Bosnian&quot; in Croatia obeying laws and voting).</segment>
    <segment id="54" parent="70" relname="span">

It seems to me we have to understand the enemy within science that motivates
an externalization of the enemy in the figure of the relativist STSer.</segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="65" relname="span"> And
we have to understand how this scapegoating logic is itself dependent upon
relativist tropes:</segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="62" relname="list"> they have their community,</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="62" relname="list"> it&apos;s unitary,</segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="63" relname="span"> it is founded
upon a hidden perverse enjoyment</segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="30" relname="concession"> (they talk about science,</segment>
    <segment id="30" parent="58" relname="span"> but they don&apos;t
know it!),</segment>
    <segment id="31" parent="64" relname="span"> and the construction of a &quot;threat&quot; that invites a sense of
cultural self-defense</segment>
    <segment id="32" parent="60" relname="antithesis"> (we don&apos;t care what they do,</segment>
    <segment id="33" parent="59" relname="circumstance"> but when they overstep
the bounds</segment>
    <segment id="59" parent="60" relname="span"> they want us to change our ways!)</segment>
    <segment id="34" parent="71" relname="list">

Whom does this scapegoat and marginalize within science itself?</segment>
    <segment id="35" parent="72" relname="span"> What
selective readings of science critique does it require</segment>
    <segment id="36" parent="35" relname="elaboration"> (where do Bernal, or
Lewontin, or Popper fit?)?</segment>
    <segment id="37" parent="73" relname="span"> How are we being invited to scapegoat ourselves?</segment>
    <segment id="38" parent="66" relname="disjunction">
&quot;It&apos;s the relativists that are to blame&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="39" parent="40" relname="concession"> or &quot;It&apos;s the feminists,</segment>
    <segment id="40" parent="68" relname="span"> but I&apos;ve
always politely ignored them anyway&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="41" parent="66" relname="disjunction"> or &quot;It&apos;s the politicos&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="42" parent="66" relname="disjunction"> or the
philosophers</segment>
    <segment id="67" parent="66" relname="disjunction"> or the non-relativists,</segment>
    <segment id="44" parent="66" relname="disjunction"> etc.</segment>
    <segment id="43" parent="74" relname="span"> How will we gain strength as a
community and at the expense of whom?</segment>
    <segment id="45" parent="43" relname="elaboration"> And why?</segment>
